  Remove the intermediate populations and all you have are two (related) species."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/de6920ef955a8a66496e7eccbd2e60d8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1165,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1165/mark","reputation":173,"display_name":"Mark"},"score":0,"post_id":10660,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2c33b5588bbd268ce2680853ea79b1a9?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":231,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/231/mgkrebbs","reputation":3086,"display_name":"mgkrebbs"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1380669948,"comment_id":14162,"body":"@mgkrebbs - Great comment about ring species.  Here&#39;s a nice explanation: <a href=\"http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/evolution/library/05/2/l_052_05.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">pbs.org/wgbh/evolution/library/05/2/l_052_05.html<\/a>"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e9816d55432fe78dee3e68a3f5f584fa?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4541,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4541/smith","reputation":17,"display_name":"Smith"},"score":0,"post_id":10660,"edited":false,"creation_date":1380775597,"comment_id":14174,"body":"But lets become somewhat practical. If you read from that wiki page only, it says only four species are found to follow this concept of ring species. So, again, if this is the right concept, atleast majority of species are supposed to follow it. And thus, this idea still is just a concept and not a law, which is universally applicable. Any comments?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/7baa20e2429818eb3a4a15ee1d3a7b6b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3523,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3523/mattia-rovetta","reputation":452,"display_name":"Mattia Rovetta","accept_rate":50},"score":0,"post_id":10660,"edited":false,"creation_date":1380972018,"commen