tp://www.pnas.org/content/91/12/5436.full.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">Rutledge et al<\/a>), if you treat their embrya with retinoid acid (which normally defines embryonic polarity) or fibroblast growth factor. In nature, different factors can lead to development of extra legs, and the most well-known and wide-spread cases are limb abnormalities in amphibians, induced by trematodes and pollution (including retinoid acid mimics?) (<a href=\"http://tiee.ecoed.net/vol/v2/issues/frontier_sets/amphibians/pdf/Frontiers-Blaustein-Johnson.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">Blaustein &amp; Johnson<\/a>).<\/p>\n\n<p>That said, I would not be surprised by a discovery of a fossil amphibian with extra limbs. But such a find then should be interpreted as an abnormality, if not proved otherwise. It's true that the fore and the hind limbs are serial homologues, but their number seems to have been fixed very early (in contrast to the number of the fingers).<\/p>\n","answer_id":10784,"question_id":10349,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/10349/are-there-any-6-limbed-reptile-fossils","last_activity_date":1381268667,"creation_date":1378729248,"answer_count":1,"title":"Are there any 6 limbed reptile fossils?","body":"<p>Were any 6 armed \"tetrapod\" fossils ever found? I've seen some lobe finned fish with two sets of shoulders in an evolutionary bio book... I'm curious because I'd like 4 limbed and 2 winged dragons to have existed :)<\/p>\n","question_id":10349,"tags":["evolution"],"score":3,"accepted_answer_id":10784,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":526,"up_vote_count":3},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/889ecb0791d10899d083c1959ffaaf53?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":4629,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4629/pip","reputation":15,"display_name":"PIP"},"closed_date":1381324722,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1MUb2.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registe