age, meaning that juveniles before their first flights show more diversity in wing shapes than flying juveniles and those, in turn, approach gradually the narrow variability of these parameters of the adults.<\/li>\n<li>Juvenile bats start performing their first short flights even before weaning. The main requirement for the flight ability per se is a certain threshold value of wing loading. Sustained flights start roughly half-way to maturity and correlate with the emergence of the above mentioned plateau on the growth curves. The flight abilities improve together with aerodynamic characteristics of the wing: duration of flight increases, beat frequency decreases, but beat power increases etc.<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>Some references:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/discover/10.2307/1378165\" rel=\"nofollow\">Jones (1967)<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"http://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/BF00569202\" rel=\"nofollow\">Buchler (1980)<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1469-7998.1995.tb04494.x/abstract\" rel=\"nofollow\">Hughes et al (1995)<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.ias.ac.in/jarch/jbiosci/22/193-202.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">Isaac, Marimuthu (1997)<\/a><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n","answer_id":10725,"question_id":7779,"up_vote_count":0,"last_edit_date":1380979214}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/7779/when-is-wing-growth-in-the-bat-complete-and-how-soon-can-bats-fly-after-wing-gro","last_activity_date":1380979214,"creation_date":1365212128,"answer_count":1,"title":"When is wing growth in the bat complete and how soon can bats fly after wing growth is complete?","body":"<p>I was reading <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2192750/\" rel=\"nofollow\">this paper by Cretekos et al (2008)<\/a>, in which they state that wing development in the bat is not complete until after birth - the wing continues to elongate postnatally.  This would suggest that bats are unable to fly immediately after birth, and a brief web search confirms this.<\/p>\n\n<p>However, I would like to know:<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><p>When is wing growth (by which I simply mean outward growth or extension) complete? <\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>When are bats able to fly?  (Are there other developmental processes that take place after wing extension that delay this process?)<\/p><\/li>\n<\/ol>\n","question_id":7779,"tags":["zoology","development"],"score":1,"accepted_answer_id":10725,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":128,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/exZpm.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4601,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4601/gelatinfox","reputation":11,"display_name":"GelatinFox"},"closed_date":1380958057,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1MUb2.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1306,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1306/terdon","reputation":9339,"display_name":"terdon","accept_rate":73},"score":2,"post_id":10722,"edited":false,"creation_date":1380946081,"comment_id":14226,"body":"Sorry but this is not a real question. What makes you <i>you<\/i>? If you have different characteristics how can you be <i>you<\/i>? Also, the egg does not choose sperm, where did you get that idea?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/exZpm.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4601,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4601/gelatinfox","reputation":11,"display_name":"GelatinFox"},"score":0,"post_id":10722,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1MUb2.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1306,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1306/terdon","reputation":9339,"display_name":"terdon","accept_rate":73},"edited":false,"creation_date":1380946951,"comment_id":14229,"body":"I, as in being an entity that can perceive the world. Let&#39;s Ignore the extra features like hair, eye color, etc."},{"own