/p>\n\n<p>This reaction is highly variable from one individual to the next and can have no effect or cause further surgery or rejection of the implant.  <a href=\"http://www.medicinenet.com/script/main/art.asp?articlekey=155237\" rel=\"nofollow\">the cause is poorly understood and so diagnosis is still in an exploratory state<\/a>. <\/p>\n\n<p>Since oxidation and rust seem to cause more irritation, it seems that corrosion resistance is an important part of implant metal choices.   Hardness, durability and Cost is also an issue since I'm sure gold and platinum would also be great choices from a cost perspective. <\/p>\n","answer_id":10706,"question_id":10662,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/10662/what-makes-a-metal-safe-to-use-for-an-artificial-joint","last_activity_date":1380826997,"creation_date":1380625841,"answer_count":3,"title":"What makes a metal safe to use for an artificial joint?","body":"<p>What determines if a metal is suitable for transplantation such as in the hip? What I am most interested in however is why might some metals be toxic to animals once in the body?<\/p>\n","question_id":10662,"tags":["biochemistry","medicinal-chemistry"],"score":4,"accepted_answer_id":10668,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":257,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1380632132},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/ole3i.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4592,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4592/pandora","reputation":141,"display_name":"Pandora"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/7baa20e2429818eb3a4a15ee1d3a7b6b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3523,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3523/mattia-rovetta","reputation":452,"display_name":"Mattia Rovetta","accept_rate":50},"score":1,"post_id":10684,"edited":false,"creation_date":1380752963,"comment_id":14172,"body":"I found <a href=\"http://ir.uiowa.edu/c