be another matter.<br>\nAlso, some of the algal blooms are poisonous \"red tides.\"<\/p>\n","answer_id":10593,"question_id":10584,"up_vote_count":2},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/889548c1e8387b3d381853dee5212cfd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3632,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3632/shigeta","reputation":22684,"display_name":"shigeta","accept_rate":86},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5ac71c8033f4b2b7d9f8ccc679bbea5c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":146,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/146/dale","reputation":707,"display_name":"Dale","accept_rate":33},"score":0,"post_id":10642,"edited":false,"creation_date":1380561823,"comment_id":14133,"body":"The iron dumping was shown to be quickly removed from the seawater through its incorporation into some component of the algae that then sank: much like nitrogen. I think the iron might have been incorporated into a shell of some sort as part of the algae--possibly mixed in with CaCO3 or something. That was the reason Iron dumping was abandoned: it was hoped the iron would remain in the ocean ecosystem for longer."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/889548c1e8387b3d381853dee5212cfd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3632,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3632/shigeta","reputation":22684,"display_name":"shigeta","accept_rate":86},"score":0,"post_id":10642,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5ac71c8033f4b2b7d9f8ccc679bbea5c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":146,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/146/dale","reputation":707,"display_name":"Dale","accept_rate":33},"edited":false,"creation_date":1380567607,"comment_id":14137,"body":"My point is just that your proposal is probably deserving of more thought - similar sorts of ques