en water content will be balanced. That is the reason why we use artificial face moisturizer for immediate remedy to avoid infection and balance the wetness of face. So it takes a while for the skin to get back to normal state if nothing is done after shaving which sometime leads to acne or rashes due to infection.<\/p>\n\n<p>Another reason for dry face is use of hot water which removes skin oil instantaneously. So lukewarm water or cold water will further reduce the dryness of the skin. (Use of shaving cream with high alkaline content will obviously result in dry skin. This holds for soaps also.)<\/p>\n\n<p>Complete details can be found in the first link provided and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/301811-my-skin-is-dry-after-shaving/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Drying skin after shave<\/a>.<\/p>\n","answer_id":10594,"question_id":10524,"up_vote_count":2}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/10524/why-does-shaving-dehydrate-the-skin-is-there-an-hormonal-effect-involved","last_activity_date":1380231808,"creation_date":1379792951,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why does shaving dehydrate the skin? Is there an hormonal effect involved?","body":"<p>I want to understand why the face becomes dry after shaving and if shaving affects hormones? I've heard that after shaving, hair grows back faster, why? Shaving damages hair follicles and they become inflamed. One could get an infection JUST by shaving because tissue is ripped from the hair follicles. So maybe the increase in hair growth can be attributed to the natural blood rush that brings nutrients to the damaged follicles when they are inflamed after shaving....<\/p>\n","question_id":10524,"tags":["human-biology","human-anatomy"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":1,"is_answered":true,"view_count":1129,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1379869469},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/71b5177a738460e6c1c9dca5a04fb0db?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4478,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4478/greg","reputation":163,"display_name":"Greg","accept_rate":75},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/GqkqP.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4101,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4101/amory","reputation":7383,"display_name":"Amory"},"score":2,"post_id":10551,"edited":false,"creation_date":1379990283,"comment_id":13994,"body":"Presumably $r$ (or $-r$) is the rate, which would appear to stay constant."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/v5upF.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3624,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3624/fileunderwater","reputation":10502,"display_name":"fileunderwater"},"score":3,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1380019719,"creation_date":1380019211,"body":"<p>$r$ is the individual mortality rate per time step. Survivorship curves (plotted on a log scale) show the proportion of individuals surviving with time, and with a Type II curve a constant proportion is dying at each time step (constant mortality with age, $r$). When the model is expressed as $y$ you are looking at the number of individuals surviving to a time step, which is an negative exponential for Type II, since a smaller and smaller proportion of the population remains at each time step. Therefore $y'$ is the change (slope) in the number of individuals surviving over time. This can be seen as a rate, but it is not the mortality rate of individuals, and it is not accurate to describe it as the \"..<em>real mortality rate..<\/em>\".   <\/p>\n\n<p>For an introduction to survivorship curves you can also look at <a href=\"http://www.nature.com/scitable/knowledge/library/survivorship-curves-16349555\" rel=\"nofollow\" title=\"Rauschert, E. (2010) Survivorship Curves. Nature Education Knowledge 3(10):18\">\"Survivorship Curves\" from Nature Education<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":10555,"question_id":10551,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1380019719},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/15f9d8beda0341f0a97ab2f4e63d094e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":67,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/67/fomite","reputation":2369,"display_name":"Fomite"},"score":0,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1380207056,"creation_date":1380207056,"body":"<p>This is a statistical property of the curve - in time to event analysis (which is what a survivorship curve is), a constant hazard (the instantaneous probability of an event occurring in time t given it has not occurred already) will yield an exponentially distributed survival function. When graphed on a log axis, this function looks like a straight line.<\/p>\n","answer_id":10589,"question_id":10551,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/10551/survivorship-curves-type-ii-curve-mortality-rate-is-not-constant","last_activity_date":1380207056,"creation_date":1379986898,"answer_count":2,"title":"Survivorship Curves: Type II curve mortality rate is not constant?","body":"<p>In graphs of survivorship curves, I'm seeing that the Type II curves are straight lines, and the supplementary text says that the mortality rate is constant (i.e. the slope of the line is constant). However, it's also clearly stated that the y-axis is a logarithmic scale, which means that the original Type II curve is exponential:\n$$\\ln y=-rx+b$$\n$$y=Ae^{-rx}$$<\/p>\n\n<p>This implies that the real mortality rate is not constant, but changes as $$y'=-Ar(e^{-rx})$$\nHow are we defining the word <em>rate<\/em>, anyway?<\/p>\n","question_id":10551,"tags":["ecology","mathematical-models","demography"],"score":3,"accepted_answer_id":10555,"down_vote_count":1,"is_answered":true,"view_count":633,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1380022890},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/7974275b33c1c13d775152e812b35776?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":558,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/558/kirby","reputation":619,"display_name":"Kirby","accept_rate":52},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/934a90404fe944a01135142de991d393?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4199,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4199/von-mises","reputation":746,"display_name":"von Mises"},"score":1,"post_id":10549,"edited":false,"creation_date":1380123734,"comment_id":14039,"body":"I may be wrong but to get the number of possible genotypes isnt it 4+3+2+1=10?. You can have A1A1,A1A2,A1A3,A1A4,A2A2,A2A3,A2A4 and so on. When you multiply you are counting some genotypes twice (for example A1A2 and A2A1. They are the same)"}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/GqkqP.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4101,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4101/amory","reputation":7383,"display_name":"Amory"},"score":2,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1380148163,"creation_date":1380127659,"body":"<p>Those Hardy-Weinberg equations are the general case, used for only two alleles.  This question is basically <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/q/8499/4101\">answered here, for three alleles<\/a>; you've got a situation of four alleles.  That means you need to have:<\/p>\n\n<p>$(p+q+r+s)^2=1$<\/p>\n\n<p>Where $p$, $q$, $r$, and $s$ are the frequencies of your respective alleles.  This expands out to the rather unwieldy:<\/p>\n\n<p>$p^2+2pq+2pr+2ps+q^2+2qr+2qs+r^2+2rs+s^2=1$<\/p>\n\n<p>Now it becomes a plug 'n chug assignment; simply assign the frequencies and calculate.<\/p>\n\n<blockquote class=\"spoiler\">\n  <p> Assuming $p$ is Adh-1, $q$ is Adh-2, etc., $p^2=0.0121$, $2pq=0.1848$, and so on.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n","answer_id":10580,"question_id":10549,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1380148163}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/10549/possible-genotypes-of-4-