 cells.  Think of how there is a certain error rate associated with DNA replication - so even from that very first cell, when it divides to form a second cell, there is a chance there may be mutations in the DNA copy.  It is highly unlikely that both twins will make the same mistake in copying the DNA in exactly the same location.  Now repeat that idea millions and millions of times, as they develop, forming all the cells they need to form their bodies, and throughout their lives.  Mutations are random, and they accumulate.<\/p>\n\n<p>I made a video about this topic - <a href=\"http://youtu.be/gkwN4eXU7yA\" rel=\"nofollow\">Are Identical Twins Really Identical?<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":10546,"question_id":10544,"up_vote_count":2}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/10544/are-identical-twins-exactly-the-same","last_activity_date":1379970998,"creation_date":1379955226,"answer_count":2,"title":"Are identical twins exactly the same?","body":"<p><a href=\"http://www.scientificamerican.com/article.cfm?id=identical-twins-genes-are-not-identical\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.scientificamerican.com/article.cfm?id=identical-twins-genes-are-not-identical<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>According to this article some identical twins show differences with respect to their copy number variants. How is this possible? If mitosis of an egg can lead to this difference, why can't mitosis of any cell in our body?<\/p>\n\n<p>If we assume that identical twins are exactly identical, then if we make a clone of a twin will all three be exactly identical?<\/p>\n","question_id":10544,"tags":["genetics","reproduction","mitosis","twins"],"score":4,"accepted_answer_id":10545,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":448,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1379970998},{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"user3130"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ab24c0e23c30888c23e2d4fe9991cf2b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","use